      "writtenOn": "2017-04-06T21:04:46Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "So that’s the big question. If this call isn’t here, then there isn’t much of a reason for WinMultiprocessWithTempDir to exist as it does here at all. I don’t see a very strong case for having a class that just adds a ScopedTempDir on top of WinMultiprocess. So if we didn’t have this call here, we could get away with exposing just ScopedTempDir and just WaitForAllChildProcessesOf(), and it’d be on each test to figure out what it needs to do. It’s a little harder on the test writer because they don’t get ScopedTempDir or temp dir environment variable passing or WaitForAllChildProcessesOf() waiting on the right process handle together automatically and for free.\n\nTo split things out, we’d want test writers to have their own ScopedTempDir, ScopedEnvironmentVariable, and WaitForAllChildProcessesOf() call. Too much work?\n\nThe alternative is to go with what you’ve gotten here, which leaves us with this loose WaitForAllChildProcessesOf() that’s really just an implementation detail of WinMultiprocessWithTempDir, which argues for “private.” Then, go with the “private + static member \u003d good candidate to move it into an unnamed namespace” guideline and keep it out of sight, confine it to just the .cc, and stick it up with its buddy functions above.\n\nI’m not going to express a strong preference between the two options. I think that keeping WinMultiprocessWithTempDir as it is here is easier for the tests you’re writing today, but maybe limiting for tests that we’d want to write in the future. But we don’t have those tests yet and I’m not envisioning anything concrete, so I’m not going to try to paint us into one corner or another.",
      "revId": "8cedea10186ac999991887766515b615281d7a21",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
